title: For Sale:  10/22 reliability and accuracy work.
postcontent:
It's well known that the Ruger 10/22 has one of the stiffest trigers in the industry, typically between 7 and 9 pounds from the factory.  Other issues include failure to feed and extraction problems.  

I will polish all friction points in both the trigger group and the bolt.
I'll reshape the nose of the firing pin and polish the stamped edges.
I'll polish the trigger return spring plunger and the mating surface on the trigger.
I will reshape the extractor and stone and polish it for positive extraction.
I will rework the bolt release so you can release the bolt by simply pulling it back. 
        Never again will you have to fumble with the finicky bolt release.
I will polish and radius the factory hammer and stone the hammer hook.
I will polish and reshape the sear for a crisp and light engagement. 
I will install an overtravel adjustment screw on the trigger.

When this is done you will have a rifle with a 3 pound trigger +/- a couple of ounces with all the original factory springs, safety checked and 100% reliable.  The improved trigger will improve your accuracy and enjoyment of the rifle.  

Other work can be done upon request, 

I can shim the hammer, sear and diconnector.  Shiming the parts makes disassembly and reassambly of the trigger group a real challenge for  those not familar with the process.  

I can drill an access hole at the back of the receiver to allow you to clean the rifle from the breach instead of the muzzel. 

I can install a recoil buffer to protect the bolt and receiver as well.

I can polish and tune the factory magazines for smoother operation and improved feeding.

All the above work is for a rifle intended for casual target shooting and hunting.

title: For Sale:  RE: For Sale: PRICE DROP!!!!! 22 Long Rifle Eley Ammo 22lr BEWARE!!
postcontent:
This stuff is pure crap! Eley will even say so when they refuse to replace it for being crap. They are boxing up their rejects and selling it as "practice", then telling customers if they don't like it, they should upgrade at their own expense. 
Read this thread.
http://discussions.texasbowhunter.com/forums/archive/index.php/t-80009.html
Here is the reply one unsatisfied customer got.

"Dear Mr Kelly Edwards,

I have received the following response from our Quality Systems Manager, following your email:

The Practice product you are referring to is an unusual product, it is not featured in the new product range and marketing materials because it is a very low quality cartridge which we donât aim to manufacture. Every cartridge manufactured by ELEY is graded and the quality specification decides whether its Tenex grade, Match, Club and so on. Practice cartridges is a byproduct â basically cartridges which do not make even our lowest grade become Practice. With increasing production technology and quality control, we donât produce high volumes of Practice â hence we donât market it. On the occasion where we do have some practice this is sold to distributors as a special offer.

3106-30252

Looking back through our Quality records, the lot was originally proofed as Target 17 in 2006. It appears to have been downgraded to our cheapest and lowest quality product (Practice) at packing.

The performance of this low graded product can be erratic but safe. The projectiles that fail to reach the target appear to do so because they have insufficient energy. Such performance is often seen (this comment really bothers me)with Practice and can be the reason for being graded Practice. Our recommendation would be to try our Target or Club grade ammo as there are better options for target practice.

Kind Regards

Kate White

Marketing Manager

Eley Limited"

For Sale/Trade:  RARE Marlin 336RC with a rare Serial number
postcontent: ***TRADED***For sale or trade, I have a Marlin 336RC chambered in 35 Remington. In 1969 Marlin changed their serial number code from the first 2 characters being letters to indicate the year mfgd. from 69 on, the first 2 characters were the last 2 numbers of the four digit year mfgd., however, there were a very few that got stamped "68" before the 1969 productions started, this rifle is one of those guns. I have talked to several Marlin collectors who have dozens of these 336 lever guns and they tell me that a "68" serial number doesn't exist and the 1968 productions all have AD for the first 2 characters. No one can tell me how many of these were made but from my research, it's a pretty good bet that you can go through all guns in your collection and your buddy's collection and you won't find a single one. I am asking $875 firm , prefer cash but will entertain offers of guns of interest. Thanks for looking in...............BTW, this rifle is in near mint condition, wood is fantastic, and bluing is close to 100%. Very nice for a 1968 model. (45 years old)
